# dataset is 11 fields (986 rows) regarding the attributes of Pokemons 
# X/independent variables:
#   Name - string - will not use this in the mechanics below
#   Total - int
#   HP - int (note: HP is hit power)
#   Attack -  int
#   Sp_attack - integer 
#   Sp_defence - integer 
#   Speed - integer

# Y/dependent variable:
#   Defence - int -the number that represents the defensive capabilities of the character

df = pd.read_csv(r'C:\Users\tamle\Desktop\Utica\2 - MSDS Summer 2021\DSC-609 Machine Learning\week 8\pokemon.csv')
# clean the data
df[df == np.inf] = np.nan
df == df.dropna()
# summary of the raw data
print(df)

# declare the X & Y variables for our dataframe df 

X = df[['Total',   'HP',  'Attack',  'Sp_attack',  'Sp_defence', 'Speed']].values
Y = df[['Defence']].values.ravel()
Y = np.array(Y).astype(int)
X = preprocessing.scale(X)
In [9]:
# first strategy for classifying the data = knn - k nearest neighbors

kNN = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = 4)
kNN_accuracy = cross_val_score(kNN, X, Y, scoring = 'accuracy', cv = 10).mean()
kNN_accuracy

# let's fit the ridge regression

from sklearn.model_selection import RepeatedKFold
from sklearn.linear_model import RidgeCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LassoCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import statsmodels.api as sm
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

lambdas = 10**np.linspace(10,-2,100)
fold = RepeatedKFold(n_splits = 10, n_repeats = 1, random_state = 1)
ridge = RidgeCV(alphas = lambdas, cv = fold, normalize = True)
ridge.fit(X, Y)
